      • parse

        public static ATime parse(String timeString)
                   throws IllegalArgumentException
        Returns a new ATime constructed from a time specification string. The time specifier indicates the values for the fields that make up the time. These fields are the hour, the minute, the second and the fractional part of the second, the nanosecond. If a field is left unspecified, a zero value is used by default.

        The time specifier takes the form:

        HH[[:]mm[[:]ss[.nano]]]

        Where:
        HH - the hour from 00 to 23.
        mm - the minute from 00 to 59.
        ss - the second from 00 to 59.
        nano - the fractional part up to 9 digits.
        The hour is the only required field. The colons (:) may be omitted as long as the HH, mm, and ss fields are composed of 2 digits each. If a nano field is included, the decimal point (.) must be included as well.

        Examples:

        10
        1030
        10:30
        10:30:45
        10:30:45.123456789
        103045.123456789
        Parameters:
        timeString - the time specifier
        Returns:
        a new ATime
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the time specification is invalid

      • format

        public String format(String pattern)
        Formats the time based on pattern keywords. The pattern is scanned for keywords that are replaced by the indicated value or text. The valid keywords include the following:

        • Hour - the hour of the day as a 24 hour value (no leading zero).
        • hour - the hour of the day as a 12 hour value (no leading zero).
        • HH - 2 digit hour in 24 hour format.
        • hh - 2 digit hour in 12 hour format.
        • Minute - the minute of the hour value (no leading zero).
        • minute - 2 digit minute.
        • mm - same as "minute".
        • Second - the second of the hour value (no leading zero).
        • second - 2 digit second.
        • ss - same as "second".
        • Nano - the nanosecond of the second value (no leading zeroes).
        • nano - 9 digit nanosecond of second.
        • micro - 6 digit microsecond of second.
        • milli - 3 digit millisecond of second.
        • nn1 - 3 digit 1st group of nanosecond.
        • nn2 - 3 digit 2nd group of nanosecond.
        • nn3 - 3 digit 3rd group of nanosecond.
        • AMPM - Uppercase AM/PM indicator.
        • ampm - Lowercase am/pm indicator.

        Other characters appearing in the pattern are copied without translation. To protect text that may contain segments that make up a keyword, place the text between angle brackets as in <the second time>.

        Examples:

        HH:mm:ss.nano => 20:30:05.123456789
        hh:mm ampm => 08:30 pm
        <Hour:> Hour <Minute:> Minute => Hour: 20 Minute: 30
        HH mm ss - nn1.nn2.nn3 => 20 30 05 - 123.456.789
        <Milliseconds:> milli => Milliseconds: 123
        <Microseconds:> micro => Microseconds: 123456
        Parameters:
        pattern - the format pattern
        Returns:
        a formatted string
